=> Monolithic vs Microservices Architecture
    -> What is Monolithic Architecture?
        -> A monolithic application is built as one single unit, where all features are tightly coupled and deployed together.
        -> For Example: E-commerce App
            -> User Service
            -> Product Service
            -> Order Service
            -> Payment Service
            -> Notification Service
        -> Example:
                                Client
                                   |
                        -----------------------------
                        |        Monolith App       |
                        |  Users | Orders | Payment |
                        |  Products | Notification  |
                        -----------------------------
                                    |
                                Single DB

        -> Advantage: Simple to develop, Easy deployment, Easy debugging, Performance
        -> Disadvantages: Tight coupling, Poor scalability, Slower development at scale, Single point of failure

    -> What is Microservices Architecture?
        -> Microservices architecture breaks the application into small, independent services, each responsible for one business capability.
        -> Same example:
                                                  Client
                                                    |
                                                  API Gateway
                                                    |
                                    ------------------------------------------------
                                    |   User   |  Product  |  Order  |  Payment   |
                                    | Service  |  Service  | Service |  Service   |
                                    ------------------------------------------------
                                         |          |           |          |
                                       User DB   Product DB   Order DB   Payment DB

        -> Advantage:
            -> Independent deployment: Deploy Order service without touching Payment
            -> Independent scaling: Scale only high-traffic services
            -> Fault isolation: Payment down ≠ whole system down
            -> Technology flexibility: Java for Order, Node.js for Notification
            -> Faster team productivity: Teams work independently

        -> Disadvantages of Microservices
            -> High Complexity: Network call, service discovery, load balancing
            -> Distributed system problems: CAP theorem, Latency, Partial Failure
            -> Data consistency issues: No single DB, Need Saga / Eventual consistency
            -> Operational overhead: Monitoring, Logging, Tracing

=> Types: There are 4 main type of Microservices Design Patterns
    -> Decomposition Pattern: In this we will split/decompose our system into multiple services.
        -> How we split a system into services
            -> Decompose by Business Capability
                -> Microservices should be decomposed by business capability, not by technical layers.
                    -> For Example: E-commerce system: User Service, Order Service, Payment Service, Inventory Service
                    -> Flow Diagram:
                                Client
                                  |
                                Order Service → Payment Service → Inventory Service

            -> Decompose by Subdomain (DDD - Domain-Driven Design)
                -> Split services based on bounded contexts. For Example:
                    -> Catalog Context → Product Service
                    -> Sales Context → Order Service
                    -> Billing Context → Payment Service
                -> Important: Subdomain decomposition comes from Domain-Driven Design and focuses on domain boundaries.

    -> Communication Pattern:
        -> In a microservices architecture, services are independent processes, so they must communicate over the network.
        -> Communication patterns define how this interaction is designed to ensure scalability, reliability, and maintainability.
        -> Microservices communication patterns include API Gateway for client interaction, synchronous communication for immediate consistency, asynchronous communication for scalability and resilience, and service discovery for dynamic service location.
            -> API Gateway Pattern: The API Gateway Pattern provides a single entry point for all client requests and routes them to appropriate backend microservices.
                   -> Without API Gateway: When clients communicate directly with multiple microservices
                        -> Clients must know the address of each service
                        -> Clients may need to make multiple network calls
                        -> Authentication, logging, and rate limiting are duplicated
                        -> Any service change impacts the client
                   -> This increases client-side complexity and tight coupling.
                   -> With API Gateway:
                        -> API Gateway act as facade that Handles routing, authentication, rate limiting and also Hides internal service structure from clients
                                Client
                                  |
                                API Gateway
                                  |
                                ------------------------------
                                | User | Order | Payment | ... |
                                ------------------------------
            -> Synchronous Communication Pattern (REST / gRPC): In synchronous communication, one service sends a request to another service and waits for the response before continuing.
                -> Problem Statement: Some business flow require immediate response and strong consistency and sequential execution.
                -> For Example: Order service must confirm payment before placing an order.
                -> Solution: Service communicate using blocking protocol such as: REST(HTTP), gRPC
                                Order Service
                                      |
                                      | (REST / gRPC call)
                                      v
                                Payment Service
                                      |
                                   Response
                -> Synchronous communication is simple but tightly couples services and increases failure risk.

            -> Asynchronous Communication Pattern (Event-Driven)
                -> In asynchronous communication, services communicate by publishing events without waiting for immediate responses.
                -> Synchronous calls cause high latency, cascading failure and reduced availability. Some systems can tolerate eventual consistency.
                -> Solution: Use message brokers (Kafka, RabbitMQ) where Producer publishes events and Consumers react independently
                                Order Service
                                      |
                                      | Publish Event
                                      v
                                 Message Broker (Kafka)
                                      |
                                ---------------------------
                                | Payment | Inventory | Notification |
                                ---------------------------
                -> Asynchronous communication improves resilience and scalability at the cost of immediate consistency.

            -> Service Discovery Pattern: The Service Discovery Pattern allows services to dynamically find the network location of other services.
                -> In microservices, Services scale up/down dynamically, IP addresses change frequently, Hardcoding service locations is impossible
                -> Solution: Use service Registery.

    -> Data Management Pattern:
        -> Microservices are independently deployable, so data ownership and consistency become major challenges.
        -> Data management patterns address how services store, access, and synchronize data.
            -> Database per Service Pattern:
                -> The Database per Service Pattern states that each microservice must own its database, and no other service is allowed to access it directly.
                -> Suppose multiple services share a single database:
                    -> Schema changes impact multiple services
                    -> Tight coupling is introduced
                    -> Independent deployment is impossible
                    -> One service failure can affect others
                -> So, solution is Each microservice maintains its own private database, and data sharing happens only via APIs or events.
                -> Database per service ensures loose coupling and independent evolution of microservices.

        -> Saga Pattern: The Saga Pattern manages data consistency across multiple services by breaking a transaction into a sequence of local transactions.
            -> In this Each service performs its local transaction and publishes an event. If a step fails, compensating transactions are executed and rollback done.
            -> Saga provides data consistency in microservices without using distributed transactions.
            -> Saga Type:
                -> Choreography - services communicate via events
                -> Orchestration - a central coordinator controls flow

        -> CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation): CQRS separates write operations (commands) from read operations (queries) into different models.
            -> In CQRS, a command changes system state, while a query only reads data and does not modify it.
            -> In traditional application design, the same data model is often used for both read and write operations.
            -> As the system grows, this approach leads to several issues:
                -> Read operations become complex due to business rules embedded in the write model
                -> Write performance degrades because the model must also support heavy queries
                -> Scaling becomes difficult since read and write workloads have different characteristics
            -> This tight coupling of reads and writes limits performance, scalability, and maintainability.
            -> Reason for the Problem:
                -> Read and write operations have fundamentally different requirements:
                    -> Writes require validation, business logic, and consistency
                    -> Reads require fast, optimized data access
                -> Using a single model forces one side to compromise for the other.
            -> Solution:
                -> CQRS addresses this problem by separating concerns:
                    -> Command Model: Handles create, update, and delete operations. Focuses on business rules and data consistency
                    -> Query Model: Handles read-only operations. Uses denormalized or optimized data structures for fast access
            -> The two models can evolve independently and scale independently.
                    Client
                      |
                    ---------------------------
                    |                         |
                    Command API            Query API
                      |                         |
                    Write Model            Read Model
                      |                         |
                    Write DB               Read DB


    -> Resilience & operational patterns:
        -> Resilience patterns prevent cascading failures at runtime, while operational patterns ensure safe deployment, monitoring, and recovery in production. Together, they enable systems to fail gracefully instead of catastrophically.
        -> Resilience: In a distributed system or microservices architecture, failures are not exceptional events—they are normal and inevitable.
                       Failures can happen due to:
                            -> Network latency or packet loss
                            -> Partial service outages
                            -> Slow downstream dependencies
                            -> Infrastructure issues (CPU spikes, GC pauses, node restarts)
                       So, Resilience is the ability of a system to handle failures and still provide service instead of completely breaking.
                       Resilience does not mean zero failure. It means controlled failure without cascading impact.

        -> Why Resilience Patterns Are Required:
            -> In a monolithic system, a failure usually stays within the same process. In microservices: Service A → Service B → Service C → Service D
            -> If Service D slows down, then:
                -> Threads in C get blocked
                -> Thread pools in B fill up
                -> Service A becomes unresponsive
            -> This is called cascading failure.
            -> Resilience patterns exist to:
                -> Detect failures early
                -> Isolate failures
                -> Prevent failure propagation
                -> Recover gracefully
        -> Core Resilience Patterns
            -> Circuit Breaker Pattern
            -> Retry Pattern (With Backoff)
            -> Timeout Pattern
            -> Bulkhead Pattern
            -> Rate Limiting (Protective Resilience)

        -> Operational Patterns (Beyond Runtime Resilience)
        -> Health Check Pattern
        -> Monitoring & Observability Pattern
        -> Graceful Degradation Pattern
        -> Deployment Safety Patterns (Operational Resilience)
